    a_en: "Diamond problem: a class inherits from two parents with a common ancestor — ambiguity about which method to call. Java resolves this: (1) no multiple class inheritance (single `extends`). (2) interfaces allow multiple implementation (resolved via explicit method override). With Java 8 default methods: if both interfaces B and C define the same method, the subclass must explicitly override it. This design eliminates ambiguity and prevents runtime method resolution errors.",
