    a_en: "`volatile` ensures variable reads/writes go directly to/from main memory, not CPU caches, guaranteeing thread visibility. Changes are immediately visible to all threads. Use for: flags, initialization checks. \n\n**Example:** `volatile boolean stopFlag;`. NOT suitable for compound operations — `count++` is still non-atomic even with volatile. `volatile` only provides visibility, not atomicity or synchronization. Use `AtomicInteger` when atomicity is needed.",
